If you followed my previous article on the high-level concepts of Clean Architecture, you know the goal: separating concerns so your code doesn’t become a tangled mess.
But today, we are getting into the actual implementation: The Domain Layer.
It starts with a single feature request.
A new developer joins a project, opens up a component file, and needs to fetch some data. So, they call an API directly inside the component. Then they need to validate a form or transform a data response, so they write that logic right next to the UI code.
It is incredibly easy to dive in, go wild, and build features at lightning speed in month one. But six months later, that single component is 1000 lines long. Nobody wants to touch it.
Worse yet, it makes the application incredibly fragile and difficult to test. As software engineers, what we do carries a lot of responsibility — our code has real-world impact, and bugs can have serious financial or safety consequences.
We tend to think that when we press a brake pedal in a modern car, we are controlling a mechanical lever. We aren’t. We are sending a signal to an onboard computer. There have been cases where software bugs in these systems led to serious injuries.
Thorough testing is not a luxury; it is a requirement.
To test logic, that logic must be extractable. This is why the Domain Layer is the most important part of your architecture.
The Domain Layer is framework-agnostic
Think of the Domain Layer as your Entities, DTOs, and business rules in their purest form. There is no React. There is no API. There are no external libraries.
If you extracted just this layer, another developer could read it and understand your entire business logic without knowing a single thing about your tech stack. The core business logic should be able to express itself without referencing other layers of the system.
When implementing this on the frontend, I take a pragmatic approach. In a backend environment, you might use classes to define entities and their rules. In React, forcing classes into your domain often feels unnatural and overcomplicated.
Keep it simple: define your entities as types and your business rules as pure functions.
The business rules within this layer are often just simple, pure utility functions. They take data in, perform a calculation or a validation, and return a result. Because they don’t rely on a browser or a framework, they are incredibly easy to unit test.
// core/domain/types/Product.ts
export type ProductStatus = 'draft' | 'published' | 'archived';export interface Product {
id: string;
name: string;
status: ProductStatus;
price: number;
}
export function isAvailableForPurchase(product: Product): boolean {
return product.status === 'published' && product.price > 0;
}
This is the domain layer. One file. Pure TypeScript. First, we define what a product status can be — draft, published, or archived. That’s it. No API response shape. No component prop. Just the vocabulary of the business.
Then the Product itself. An id, a name, a status, a price. This is what a product is in your system — not what the API returns, not what the UI renders. What it fundamentally is.
And then this function — isAvailableForPurchase. It takes a product and returns a boolean. A product is available if it’s published and the price is greater than zero. One line. One rule.
Now look at the imports at the top of this file. There are none.
No React. No fetch. No third-party library. Nothing from the outside world. If you rip React out of your project tomorrow and replace it with Vue or Svelte or anything else — this file does not change. Not a single line. That’s the whole point of the domain layer. It’s the part of your codebase that belongs to the business, not to the framework.
Entities are not DTOs
One of the most common mistakes is using the same structure for your API response and your application state. If you use TanStack Query to simply mirror the server response, you are tightly coupling your frontend to your backend’s implementation details.
In real-world systems, data is rarely clean. You are often ingesting data from legacy systems or third-party APIs where the data is unnormalized. You might find JSON strings embedded inside a metadata field, or numbers represented as strings.
The moment you modify the structure of the data to suit your UI, it is no longer “server state.” It is application state.
What are DTOs?
DTO stands for Data transfer object. A DTO is a stateless data structure designed exclusively to carry raw data across the boundaries of different application layers. Its primary job is to ensure that the core Domain Layer (Entities and Use Cases) remains completely decoupled.
In simple terms, your API request/response objects or the partial temporary objects you construct when you call some service is a DTO. Think about like DTO is just a fancy name for a temporary object.
If you don’t transform this data at the boundary, you will end up with “If-Else Hell” — your UI components will be littered with if (type === 'tire') or JSON.parse(metadata) logic.
In complex apps, you often need to transform a DTO into an Entity. You might need to combine data from two different endpoints or parse raw strings into proper formats.
If this was for a tire shop store, then you would typically have several types of products like tire, rim, service..etc. The API might return a generic product structure:
// dto/ProductDTO.ts
export type ProductDTO = {
id: string;
sku: string;
// Unnormalized data: extra info is trapped as key->value pairs
metadata: Record<string, string>;
price: number;
vat_group_id: string;
};You cannot run business logic on a structure that looks like this. To make this usable, we need a mapper that transforms this DTO into a specific, strongly-typed Entity. In this case, we would normalize the data, parse the metadata and combine the VAT and price with VAT.
// domain/Tire.ts
export type TireProduct = {
id: string;
sku: string;
width: number;
rimSize: number;
aspectRatio: number;
speedRating: SpeedRating;
price: number;
vatGroup: number;
priceWithVat: number;
// rest of the properties
};// The mapper handles the "dirty" work of parsing and transformation.
export function mapProductDTOToTire(dto: ProductDTO, vatRates: Record<string, number>): Tire {
// We parse the unnormalized JSON string once, at the boundary.
const metadata = JSON.parse(dto.metadata_string);
return {
id: dto.id,
width: Number(metadata.width),
rimSize: Number(metadata.rim_size),
price: dto.price,
// We resolve the VAT rate here so the UI doesn't have to.
vatRate: vatRates[dto.vat_group_id] ?? 0,
//... rest of the code
};
}
In this example, the TireProduct entity is clean. The width is already a number, and the vatRate is already resolved. The component doesn't need to know how to parse JSON or look up VAT groups. It only cares about the Tire object.
By performing this transformation, you create a single place to handle errors and parsing logic. If the tire shop later adds a product type that requires calculating price per hour, ex: a “Service” like: tire change, wheel balancing, tire repair — Puncture…etc. you don’t change your components; you only update your domain logic.
If you continue using the DTOs, then you will end up having if else cases everywhere in the codebase. Have a separate dedicated type, would make it much easier to have a clear separation upfront and would influence how you write your components and test everything easily. That’s why keeping your logic centralized is so important.
When not to use this
Do not over-engineer simple CRUD apps. If your application is just a thin wrapper around an API — displaying a list and a delete button — adding a Domain Layer, DTOs, and mappers is a waste of time.
Only introduce these boundaries when the complexity of your business rules or the messiness of your data justifies the boilerplate.
If your logic is purely presentational, keep it in the component. If your logic involves parsing, calculations, or complex state transitions, move it to the domain.
